 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Jeddia</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/29/2003&nbsp;: 05:50:08 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Good stuff so far.  And Sleppen, those are sadly familiar stories you have.<br /><br />I am at about 65'ish missions total now, and I've spent some time with some of the "uber" guild folk.  And it's amazing who an uber guild will just dress up in expensive clothes and hurl at a mob.  <br /><br />By the same token, some of them have been awesome...truly some of the best in their class.  But sadly, some of those have that elitist attitude.  It's kind of a rarity to find one who's well geared, well skilled, *and* really friendly.<br /><br />What I'm finding more of in LDoN though, are folks like me.  People who are in medium-sized guilds who do less raiding, or raid with far less people.  This is nice, because usually these are people who are quite skilled in their class.  You can usually count on them to put in 110%.  The group of people in my guild pride themselves on doing things with minimal force - e.g., single-grouping for a BoT Tower boss or our server-first over a year ago...clearing Sleeper's Tomb with 11 people; including warders.<br /><br />Most of the uber folks are having to attend raids for their DKP's I guess. :P  And now, most of the idiots are being left in the LFG list as people are remembering them.  So LDoN is shaping up well.<br /><br />/shrug<br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Sleppen</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;09/29/2003&nbsp;: 04:13:55 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Generally, the pickup groups I've been in have been just fine.  Predictably, the biggest problem I've seen is people who cannot handle adds without a mezzer, and mezzers who can't handle adds at all.<br /><br />The most embarrassing moment came when I was in a Mistmoore group with a cleric, paladin, beastlord, shaman, and another level 65 necro.  The other necro said that he would handle mezzing, which was fine with me.  Then when we get the first add, he says "Cannot mez this mob!"  I quickly memmed Death's Silence and mezzed it.  I figured he must just have gotten a resist or something, and I let it slide.  Then we got three adds, and he said the same thing.  Fortunately, I still had Death's Silence memmed, and quickly got them under control.<br /><br />After the fight, he sends me a tell asking me how I was mezzing the mobs.  Sure enough, he didn't have Death's Silence, nor did he even know the spell existed.  We won the mission easily, and I certainly hope he made a quick trip to the Bazaar.<br /><br />The most exasperating mission was also in Mistmoore.  The other members of the group were all in fairly serious raiding guilds, and the MT was a well equipped paladin.  His pulling system was . . . well, bizarre.  Instead of just pulling the mobs and letting me mez the adds, he insisted on rooting one of the adds, which had the effect of aggroing the target mob, and then expected me to mez any other adds and then pick up the first add when the root broke.  This meant that an add would come flying into camp at some random moment during the fight.  That wouldn't have been so terrible, but he never told anyone (including me) whether he had used root to make the pull.  So we would have surprise adds flying into camp.  Most of you know that adds can be hard to target, let alone see, in Mistmoore.  As a result, I had to spend most of my time watching for adds, rather than killing the mobs.<br /><br />Eventually, his pulling technique got a couple people killed when I missed one of his adds.  Naturally, he decided to lecture me about how I was supposed to mez mobs.  I bit my tongue and just hoped that the mission would be over soon.<br /><br />This was an assassination mission, and the boss mob spawned a few minutes later.  He insisted on taking the group down the wrong corridor even though I pointed out that the tracking message showed that he was going the wrong way.  Finally, he moved back to the other corridor, clearly planning to show me that I was wrong.  The next tracking message appeared, and he said, "Well, I guess you were right."<br /><br />When we engaged the boss mob, the paladin went down like a rock.  The group's monk took over, but the fight was ugly.  I nuked like crazy, but before long the healers (two shamans) were saying "low mana" and the monk was near death.  So I lifeburned, killing the boss mob.  We didn't have a cleric, so I rezzed the paladin.  Yes, I took some satisfaction from this turn of events, but I resisted the urge to rub it in.<br /><br />After the paladin was rezzed, he said for everyone to head back to BB.  I asked, "What about the named mob we passed?"  Incredibly, this guy had not noticed a named mob that was in plain sight.  Mind you, this was a necro mob with a pet.  It sort of stood out.<br /><br />So we finished the mission by killing the named mob, which was in an area with one other mob.  I said that I'd mez the add as soon as he pulled the named.  He said no, that he would root the add to pull the named, and that I should just mez the add after it was rooted.  He starts telling me how rooting the add would insure that the named would aggro him.  I say, "Then why don't you just shoot the named with an arrow to aggro it?"  His response is that the named might aggro ME if he did that.  At this point, I was fairly exasperated, so I just said "Whatever."<br /><br />As soon as the split was done in Butcherblock, I bailed from that group and went LFG.  Ten minutes later, the paladin sends me a tell asking me to join his new group.  I politely declined.<br /><br />He really seemed like a nice enough guy, but that incident provides a valuable lesson: just because someone has fancy equipment and a prestigious guild tag, that does not mean that they have a clue what they're doing.  Fancy gear and AAs can provide phenomenal DPS, but it doesn't teach a player how to operate in a dungeon.  I've been in a number of groups with members of the top 3 or 4 guilds on my server, and they've all been excellent players who could generate DPS at a rate that is intimidating for a middle class player like me.  The players from the second tier of guilds have been pretty much of a mixed bag, and in many cases players from smaller guilds have been just as good if not better.</span></font></td>
